snippet.textDisplay:
"...And now Alesi is leading! He's got the same engine as Hill - Renault V10..." What a great new F1 regulations! I like that new V10 engines! That sounds are great for my ears! (smile)
God, how I miss these old great V10 engines with these crazy sounds... You can hear all movement on a drivers' throttle pedal here!
Let's remember all V10 engines manufacturing companies of 1996:
1. Renault RS8 3.0 V10. France. Great engine, but it was not his race;
2. Ferrari 046 3.0 V10. Italy. - It's terrible. Drives like a pig.
- Oh, you can't say that.
- Why not?
- It's a Ferrari!
- It's a sh*tbox!:DD
3. Mercedes FO 110 3,0 V10. Germany. Mercedes and other world doesn't know what a great F1 engine they will make for 1998 season and what a crappy passenger sh*tcars they will produce in 2020;
4. Mugen-Honda MF-301 HA 3.0 V10. Japan. Mugen-Honda? Who? Japanese private company that made F1 engines for Ligier, Prost and Jordan. And they still produce engines for other racing series!;
5. Yamaha OX11A 3.0 V10. Japan. 5 valves per cylinder! Other engines had only 4 per cylinder. This engine had a small advantage on slow tracks like Monaco, Hungaroring... Of course, if he'll not break;
6. Peugeot A12 EV5 3.0 V10. France. What? Peugeot produced V10 engines for F1? Yes, they did! And they were good!;
7. Ford JD Zetec-R 3.0 V10 and Ford ECA Zetec-R 3.0 V10. USA (or almost USA - it was engines produced by Cosworth in Great Britain). Ford JD was a 1st 3.0 V10 F1 engine for the company. Not bad, but not good. In 1999 their new engine will be a sensation of F1 season.
Bring that great V10 engines back, please! We don't want to hear these farting V6 Hybrid engines! Let these hybrid engines go to a hell of fart:DD
P.S.: Tyrrell Yamaha, I was your fan in this crazy race. Legendary team founder Ken Tyrrell is one of the greatest old racing enthusiast like Frank Williams, Roger Penske etc. F1 very lacks such people now. RIP Ken.

Panis deserved this win. He was the only one bold enough to overtake (@21:30 overtaking Brundle out of Rascasse!) without stuffing the car in the armco. And his team timed his switch to slicks perfectly.

snippet.textDisplay: Another fun fact about this race that this broadcast doesn't acknowledge (due to the feed) at all is that Panis actually spun on Damon Hill's oil from his blown engine and nearly crashed out. I think Panis does mention it in the post race interview but that's not included here.
